I had an issue with test 4:
My code print : MadKnight .412 when MadKnight .413 is expected, as it's the only problem all validators and others tests are ok, I think it can be due to difference with round implementation, here my code in Python:

r={}
for i in'*'*int(input()):
    n,*l = input().split()
    p,*s,w,h,c = map(int,l)
    r[n] = round(-sum(s)/(p-w-h-c),3)

for i in sorted(r,key=r.get):
    print(i, f"{-r[i]:.3f}"[1:])

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: With this clash it is possible to train some things, rounding to 3 decimal places (rounding, not truncating) and sort.

My JavaScript Solution:

const N = parseInt(readline());
x = [];
for (let i = 0; i < N; i++) {
    var inputs = readline().split(' ');
    const name = inputs[0];
    const PA = parseInt(inputs[1]);
    const S = parseInt(inputs[2]);
    const D = parseInt(inputs[3]);
    const T = parseInt(inputs[4]);
    const HR = parseInt(inputs[5]);
    const W = parseInt(inputs[6]);
    const HBP = parseInt(inputs[7]);
    const SAC = parseInt(inputs[8]);
    let battingAverage = (S+D+T+HR)/(PA-W-HBP-SAC);
    x[i] = [name, Math.round(battingAverage*1000)];
}
x.sort((a,b)=>b[1]-a[1]);
x.forEach(([name, avg])=>console.log(name, (avg+"").replace(/(...$)/g,".$1")));
